Cost Function
A standard way to solve a regression problem is with an "Cost Function" that measures how good the solution is.
The function uses the weight and bias from the model (y = wx + b) and returns an error,
based on how well the line fits a plot.
The way to compute this error is to loop through all (x,y) points in the plot,
and sum the square distances between the y value of each point and the line.
The most conventional way is to square the distances (to ensure positive values)
and to make the error function differentiable.
